allTexts.deimperfectionenotarum.translation.english[3590438400] = 'De imperfectione notarum\n\
Translator: Ronald Woodley\n\
Checked by: Jeffrey J. Dean\n\
Date established: 11 October 2013\n\
<treatise><title>A treatise on the imperfections of musical notes: set forth by Master Johannes Tinctoris, licentiate in laws and chaplain of the king of Great Sicily.</title>\n\
<prologue><heading>Prologue.</heading>\n\
To the most ardent young student of the art of music, Jacobus Frontin, Johannes Tinctoris, lowliest teacher of that art, sends his undying friendship.  Illustrious youth, with the most praiseworthy of motives you have earnestly requested that I put something down in writing for you on the imperfections of musical notes; I have decided to agree at once to your certainly just request. Indeed, so well am I disposed not only towards your own outstanding talents but in fact towards all other lovers of the fine arts, that  if they should demand from me my opinion on that matter, then I should not put off producing it. Nor, I pray, should you believe that this is a subject of trivial enquiry for me, since I have read and heard that our forebears have too little debated it, our contemporaries even less. Be so kind, therefore, as to accept this small gift, dedicated with the utmost good will to your distinguished name; and I urge you most strenuously to study its highly useful teaching, lest (may it be otherwise) you should be defiled by such imperfection of honour that what you have so laudably desired, you yourself shamelessly disdain.</prologue>\n\
<book><chapter><heading>On the definition of imperfection and the quality of notes. Book I Chapter 1 [i]</heading>\n\
Being about to deal with those imperfections of musical notes, I judged that imperfection should first be defined. Imperfection, then, is the subtraction of a third part of the full value of a whole note or of its parts. And so that this matter itself might be illuminated all the more clearly, it must first be stated that only five notes of definite value altogether are to be found in music, which in this one pentameter verse are ordered in a most artful fashion:\n\
<verse>Maxima {example}, longa {example}, breve {example}, semibreve {example}, minim {example}.</verse>\n\
Of these five notes, some are larger, others smaller. The larger notes are those that are above the lower ones; the smaller notes are those that are below the upper ones. Moreover, some notes are in different respects both larger and smaller, since they are above and below some others. Hence it is that the maxima is a larger note only, because the rest are below it. The longa is a smaller note with respect to the maxima, since the former is below the latter; but with respect to the rest, namely the breve, semibreve, and minim, it is a larger note, because it is above them. The breve is a smaller note with respect to the maxima and longa, since it is below them; but with respect to the semibreve and minim it is a larger note, because it is above them. The semibreve is a smaller note with respect to the maxima, longa, and breve, since it is below them; but with respect to the minim it is a larger note, because the former is above the latter. The minim is a smaller note only, since the rest are above it. And so it must be concluded that the maxima is a larger note of the longa, breve, semibreve, and minim; the longa is a smaller note of the maxima, a larger of the breve, semibreve, and minim; the breve is a smaller note of the maxima and longa, a larger of the semibreve and minim; the semibreve is a smaller note of the maxima, longa, and breve, a larger of the minim; the minim is a smaller note of the maxima, longa, breve, and semibreve.\n\
And hence, smaller notes are parts of larger ones; of these parts, some are neighbouring, others at one remove, others at two removes, others at three removes. Neighbouring parts are those between which and the notes of which they are such parts no larger one is situated. Thus longas are neighbouring parts of the maxima, breves of the longa, semibreves of the breve, and minims of the semibreve. Parts at one remove are those between which and the notes of which they are such parts a single larger one is found. Thus breves are parts at one remove of the maxima, semibreves of the longa, and minims of the breve. Parts at two removes are those between which and the notes of which they are such parts two larger ones are discovered. Thus semibreves are parts at two removes of the maxima, and minims of the longa. Parts at three removes are those between which and the notes of which they are such parts all the other larger ones are found. Thus minims alone are parts at three removes of the maxima. From these one must infer that the neighbouring parts of the maxima are longas, those at one remove breves, those at two removes semibreves, and those at three removes minims. The neighbouring parts of the longa are breves, those at one remove semibreves, and those at two removes minims. The neighbouring parts of the breve are semibreves, and those at one remove minims. Lastly, the neighbouring parts of the semibreve are minims.\n\
And so just one note is only whole, namely the maxima; three both whole and partial, namely the longa, breve, and semibreve; and just one only partial, namely the minim. But of these five notes, in relation to the quality of prolation, tempus, and both kinds of modus, three both imperfect and are imperfected, namely the longa, breve, and semibreve; just one note is imperfected but does not imperfect, namely the maxima; and just one note imperfects but is not imperfected, namely the minim. For smaller notes imperfect larger ones, with the result that larger notes are imperfected by smaller ones. Hence it is that the longa imperfects the maxima, and is imperfected by the breve, semibreve, and minim. The breve imperfects the maxima and longa, and is imperfected by the semibreve and minim. The semibreve imperfects the maxima, longa, and breve, and is imperfected by the minim. The maxima is imperfected by the longa, breve, semibreve, and minim, and, because it does not have a larger one, it imperfects none. The minim, on the other hand, imperfects the maxima, longa, breve, and semibreve, and because it does not have a smaller one, it is imperfected by none, as in the following example:\n\
{example}</chapter>\n\
<chapter><heading>On the imperfection of rests. Chapter 2 [ii]</heading>\n\
And since there are four of these five notes to each of which one particular rest is designated, of the same value as that of its note, namely the longa {example}, the breve {example}, the semibreve {example}, and the minim {example}, it must be understood that every rest can imperfect, but cannot be imperfected, as here:\n\
{example}\n\
Hence, however many and whatever kind of notes a longa, a breve, a semibreve, and a minim can imperfect, so many and such kind can their rests. And so a longa rest will be able to imperfect a maxima; a breve rest a maxima and longa; a semibreve rest a maxima, longa, and breve; a minim rest a maxima, longa, breve, and semibreve, as is clear here:\n\
{example}</chapter>\n\
<chapter><heading>On the thirteen general rules of imperfection. Chapter 3 [iii]</heading>\n\
First, therefore, concerning myself generally with these imperfections of musical notes, I have resolved to set out thirteen general rules.\n\
<subheading>First general rule</subheading>\n\
The first general rule is that imperfection can occur in four ways: first, with respect to the whole only; second, with respect to all or some parts or some part alone; third, with respect to the whole and some parts or some part alone; fourth, with respect to the whole and all parts at once, as here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>Second general rule</subheading>\n\
The second general rule is that whenever a note is imperfected with respect to the whole, this is by its neighbouring part; and whenever it is imperfected with respect to its parts, either this is with respect to its neighbouring parts, and then it is by its parts at one remove; or with respect to those at one remove, and then it is by those at two removes; or with respect to those at two removes, and then it is by those at three removes, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>Third general rule</subheading>\n\
The third general rule is that it makes no difference whether a note is imperfected by a united or a separated part, or by united or separated parts, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
So that this may be understood better, it must be noted that a particular note may imperfect as a united part, as here:\n\
{example}\n\
Some notes imperfect as a separated part, as here:\n\
{example}\n\
A particular note may imperfect as united parts, as here:\n\
{example}\n\
And some notes imperfect as separated parts, as here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>Fourth general rule</subheading>\n\
The fourth general rule is that imperfecting is proper to a smaller note, but being imperfected to a larger one, since neither can a larger note imperfect a smaller nor a like its like. Whence it follows that neither will a smaller note be able to be imperfected by a larger, nor a like by its like, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>Fifth general rule</subheading>\n\
The fifth general rule is that every note that is imperfected from ahead is necessarily imperfected before a larger or smaller one, because like before like cannot be imperfected, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
From which rule, too, it must be noted that likewise no note will be able to be imperfected before its own rest, just as before a like note, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>Sixth general rule</subheading>\n\
The sixth general rule is that no note can be imperfected with respect to the whole unless it is perfect in itself. Similarly, with respect to parts, it will not be able to be imperfected unless they too are perfect in themselves, since otherwise a third part that is subtracted through imperfection from the whole or from the part would not be found, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>Seventh general rule</subheading>\n\
The seventh general rule is that however many times a note will be able to be divided into three equal parts, so many times it can also be imperfected; and so it will arrive at its smallest value. For instance, the longa in perfect minor modus, perfect tempus, and major prolation is worth 27 minims, which 27 make up a number divisible into three equal parts, namely into 3 times 9. If a third part of it be taken away, namely 9, there will remain 18. But 18 can once again be divided into three equal parts, namely into 3 times 6; of which if a third part be taken away, namely 6, there will remain 12. These 12, too, likewise make up a number divisible into three parts, namely into 3 times 4; if a third part of it be taken away, namely 4, there will remain 8. But 8 cannot be divided into three equal parts. Hence the longa will persist at this value, which is its smallest, namely 8 minims, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>Eighth general rule</subheading>\n\
The eighth general rule is that a note that imperfects can be placed before or after, according to the will of the composer. If this is placed before, the note that is imperfected is imperfected “from ahead”, and if it is placed after, it is said to be imperfected “from behind”, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>Ninth general rule</subheading>\n\
The ninth general rule is that if a single smaller note is found before a larger one imperfectible by it, it does imperfect it, provided that the number has been filled up or that there are no other notes preceding, as here:\n\
{example}\n\
If, on the other hand, a single smaller note is found after a larger one imperfectible by it, it does imperfect it, whether or not there follows another larger one likewise imperfectible by it, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
Equally, if several smaller notes are found set out in imperfect number before a larger one imperfectible by them, they imperfect it in the amount that they are or can be, provided that the number has been filled up or that there are no other notes preceding. And if there are still any remaining, likewise imperfect in number, they will carry over to the nearest opportunity that they will be able to have, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
If, on the other hand, several smaller notes are found set out in imperfect number after a larger one imperfectible by them, they imperfect it in the amount that they are or can be or that removes the imperfection of their number, whether or not there follows another larger one also imperfectible by them. And if there should be any still remaining, also imperfect in number, they will carry over to the nearest opportunity that they will be able to have, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
This foregoing general rule, however, admits an exception in the case of three signs, namely the dot of division, filling in, and the ligature: for if a dot of division is attached to a group of smaller notes that otherwise according to the foregoing rule would imperfect some larger one, they will not imperfect it, but rather they will carry over to the nearest opportunity that they will be able to have, as here:\n\
{example}\n\
And if smaller notes that otherwise according to the foregoing rule would imperfect some larger one are filled in, they will not imperfect it, but rather they will be regrouped with others similarly filled in, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
If, on the other hand, smaller notes that otherwise, following this same rule, would imperfect some preceding larger one should be ligated with another larger or like one following, which along with them could not imperfect that preceding larger one, they will not imperfect it, but rather will be counted with the latter, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>Tenth general rule</subheading>\n\
The tenth general rule is that if a single note or several smaller notes placed in imperfect number are found before or after a larger one that cannot be imperfected by them – if, for instance, the larger one should be itself before its like or its rest, or it should have a dot of perfection, or it should be imperfected by others as much as it could be – they carry over to the nearest opportunity that they can have, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>Eleventh general rule</subheading>\n\
The eleventh general rule is that if a dot of division is applied to any note on its own behalf only, before its like or a smaller one, it will imperfect the first larger note that it can, unless before this one it has associates, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
If, on the other hand, a dot of division is applied to any note before its like or a smaller one, not only on its own behalf but on behalf of others, the former along with the latter will also imperfect the first larger note that they can, provided that, similarly, before this one they do not have any associates, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>Twelfth general rule</subheading>\n\
The twelfth general rule is that a note to which a dot of division is applied can be imperfected, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
On the other hand, a note to which a dot of perfection or augmentation is applied is never imperfected. And the reason is this: perfection and imperfection are opposites; but opposites cannot be in the same subject at once; therefore it is impossible for one and the same note to be at once perfect and imperfect, as here:\n\
{example}\n\
For the same reason, since according to arithmetic (and music, which is subordinate to it) addition and subtraction are opposites, but augmentation is a kind of addition and imperfection a kind of subtraction, it is impossible for one and the same note to be at once augmented and imperfected, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
Perhaps some will say, “Tinctoris presumes too much in asserting that an augmented note cannot be imperfected, since De Domarto in the tenor of his Patrem in the irregular fifth tone, and Barbingant in the tenor of his song ‘L’omme bany’, have done the opposite”, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
{example}\n\
To whom I reply, although Busnoys and many others may have imitated those, that I do not presume to find fault with people as if envying someone’s reputation, but rather, upholding friend Truth to the best of my ability, I demonstrate that they have erred. I also name those erring, lest the young, deceived by false opinion on account of the undying fame that they have created for themselves by composing so very beautifully, imitate them in this, esteeming all their achievements to be perfect, which turns out to be far otherwise. For, as the wise state, nothing is perfect in every respect.\n\
<subheading>Thirteenth general rule</subheading>\n\
The thirteenth general rule is that every note that can be both imperfected and altered, such as the longa, breve, and semibreve, if it is altered, will be able to be imperfected only with respect to some of its parts, namely only so many that the smaller notes imperfecting the larger one do not attain its value, as is demonstrated again in this example following:\n\
{example}</chapter></book>\n\
<book><chapter><heading>On the imperfections of musical notes in particular. Book II Chapter 1 [i]</heading>\n\
Now that the imperfections of musical notes have been dealt with generally, it is fitting to deal in due order with the imperfection of each one in particular. Hence let us begin first with the maxima, which is the head and chief of the rest of the notes, so we may thus proceed from greater to smaller.</chapter>\n\
<chapter><heading>On the imperfection of the maxima in perfect major modus. Chapter 2 [ii]</heading>\n\
The maxima in perfect major modus can be imperfected with respect to the whole, for then it is worth three longas, of which one will be able to be subtracted as being a third part of it, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>On the imperfection of the maxima in perfect minor modus.</subheading>\n\
Furthermore, the maxima in perfect minor modus can be imperfected with respect to two neighbouring parts or one only, because then the longa, which is its neighbouring part, is worth three breves. Hence for each longa one breve will be able to be subtracted as being a third part of it, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>On the imperfection of the maxima in perfect tempus.</subheading>\n\
Furthermore, the maxima in perfect tempus can be imperfected with respect to five, four, three, or two parts at one remove or one only, for then the breve, which is its part at one remove, is worth three semibreves. Hence for each breve one semibreve will be able to be subtracted as being a third part of it, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>On the imperfection of the maxima in major prolation.</subheading>\n\
Furthermore, the maxima in major prolation can be imperfected with respect to eleven, ten, nine, eight, seven, six, five, four, three, or two parts at two removes or one only, because then the semibreve, which is its part at two removes, is worth three minims. Hence for each semibreve one minim will be able to be subtracted as being a third part of it, as is clear here:\n\
{example}</chapter>\n\
<chapter><heading>On the fifteen methods of imperfecting the maxima. Chapter 3 [iii]</heading>\n\
And since in many pieces of music all the mensural quantities are perfect, and in others several perfect ones or one only are mixed together in no particular order with several imperfect ones or one alone, it results that the maxima can be imperfected in fifteen ways.\n\
<subheading>The first way of imperfecting the maxima.</subheading>\n\
In the first, with respect to the whole only, and this in perfect major modus, imperfect minor modus, imperfect tempus, and minor prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The second way of imperfecting the maxima.</subheading>\n\
In the second way, with respect to the neighbouring parts only, and this in imperfect major modus, perfect minor modus, imperfect tempus, and minor prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The third way of imperfecting the maxima.</subheading>\n\
In the third way, with respect to the parts at one remove only, and this in imperfect modus of both kinds, perfect tempus, and minor prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The fourth way of imperfecting the maxima.</subheading>\n\
In the fourth way, with respect to the parts at two removes only, and this in imperfect modus of both kinds, imperfect tempus, and major prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The fifth way of imperfecting the maxima.</subheading>\n\
In the fifth way, with respect to the whole and the neighbouring parts only, and this in perfect modus of both kinds, imperfect tempus, and minor prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The sixth way of imperfecting the maxima.</subheading>\n\
In the sixth way, with respect to the whole and the parts at one remove only, and this in perfect major modus, imperfect minor modus, perfect tempus, and minor prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The seventh way of imperfecting the maxima.</subheading>\n\
In the seventh way, with respect to the whole and the parts at two removes only, and this in perfect major modus, imperfect minor modus, imperfect tempus, and major prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The eighth way of imperfecting the maxima.</subheading>\n\
In the eighth way, with respect to the whole, the neighbouring parts, and the parts at one remove only, and this in perfect modus of both kinds, perfect tempus, and minor prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The ninth way of imperfecting the maxima.</subheading>\n\
In the ninth way, with respect to the whole, the neighbouring parts, and the parts at two removes only, and this in perfect modus of both kinds, imperfect tempus, and major prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The tenth way of imperfecting the maxima.</subheading>\n\
In the tenth way, with respect to the whole, the parts at one remove, and the parts at two removes only, and this in perfect major modus, imperfect minor modus, perfect tempus, and major prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The eleventh way of imperfecting the maxima.</subheading>\n\
In the eleventh way, with respect to the neighbouring parts and the parts at one remove only, and this in imperfect major modus, perfect minor modus, perfect tempus, and minor prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The twelfth way of imperfecting the maxima.</subheading>\n\
In the twelfth way, with respect to the neighbouring parts and the parts at two removes only, and this in imperfect major modus, perfect minor modus, imperfect tempus, and major prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The thirteenth way of imperfecting the maxima.</subheading>\n\
In the thirteenth way, with respect to the parts at one remove and the parts at two removes only, and this in imperfect modus of both kinds, perfect tempus, and major prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The fourteenth way of imperfecting the maxima.</subheading>\n\
In the fourteenth way, with respect to the neighbouring parts, the parts at one remove, and the parts at two removes only, and this in imperfect major modus, perfect minor modus, perfect tempus, and major prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The fifteenth way of imperfecting the maxima.</subheading>\n\
In the fifteenth way, with respect to the whole, the neighbouring parts, the parts at one remove, and the parts at two removes all at once, and this in perfect modus of both kinds, perfect tempus, and major prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}</chapter>\n\
<chapter><heading>On the imperfection of the longa in perfect minor modus. Chapter 4 [iv]</heading>\n\
The longa in perfect minor modus can be imperfected with respect to the whole, for then it is worth three breves, of which one will be able to be subtracted as being a third part of the longa, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>On the imperfection of the longa in perfect tempus.</subheading>\n\
Furthermore, the longa in perfect tempus can be imperfected with respect to two neighbouring parts or one only, because then the breve, which is its neighbouring part, is worth three semibreves. Hence for each breve one semibreve will be able to be subtracted as being a third part of it, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>On the imperfection of the longa in major prolation.</subheading>\n\
Furthermore, the longa in major prolation can be imperfected with respect to five, four, three, or two parts at one remove or one only, for then the semibreve, which is its part at one remove, is worth three minims. Hence for each semibreve one minim will be able to be subtracted as being a third part of it, as is clear here:\n\
{example}</chapter>\n\
<chapter><heading>On the seven ways of imperfecting the longa. Chapter 5 [v]</heading>\n\
And since in many pieces of music under major modus of either kind stand perfect mensural quantities of minor modus, tempus, and prolation, and in others several perfect ones or one only are mixed together in no particular order with several imperfect ones or one alone, it results that the longa can be imperfected in seven ways.\n\
<subheading>The first way of imperfecting the longa.</subheading>\n\
In the first way, with respect to the whole only, and this in major modus of either kind, perfect minor modus, imperfect tempus, and minor prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The second way of imperfecting the longa.</subheading>\n\
In the second way, with respect to the neighbouring parts only, and this in major modus of either kind, imperfect minor modus, perfect tempus, and minor prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The third way of imperfecting the longa.</subheading>\n\
In the third way, with respect to the parts at one remove only, and this in major modus of either kind, imperfect minor modus, imperfect tempus, and major prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The fourth way of imperfecting the longa.</subheading>\n\
In the fourth way, with respect to the whole and the neighbouring parts only, and this in major modus of either kind, perfect minor modus, perfect tempus, and minor prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The fifth way of imperfecting the longa.</subheading>\n\
In the fifth way, with respect to the whole and the parts at one remove only, and this in major modus of either kind, perfect minor modus, imperfect tempus, and major prolation, as here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The sixth way of imperfecting the longa.</subheading>\n\
In the sixth way, with respect to the neighbouring parts and the parts at one remove only, and this in major modus of either kind, imperfect minor modus, perfect tempus, and major prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The seventh way of imperfecting the longa.</subheading>\n\
In the seventh way, with respect to the whole, the neighbouring parts, and the parts at one remove all at once, and this in major modus of either kind, perfect minor modus, perfect tempus, and major prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}</chapter>\n\
<chapter><heading>On the imperfection of the breve in perfect tempus. Chapter 6 [vi]</heading>\n\
The breve in perfect tempus can be imperfected with respect to the whole, because then it is worth three semibreves, of which one will be able to be subtracted as being a third part of it, as is clear in this example:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>On the imperfection of the breve in major prolation.</subheading>\n\
Furthermore, the breve in major prolation can be imperfected with respect to two neighbouring parts or one only, for then the semibreve, which is its neighbouring part, is worth three minims. Hence for each semibreve one minim will be able to be subtracted as being a third part of it, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>On the three ways of imperfecting the breve.</subheading>\n\
And since in many pieces of music under major or minor modus of either kind perfect tempus and major prolation occur together, and in others imperfect tempus is mixed together with major prolation, or conversely perfect tempus with minor prolation, it results that the breve can be imperfected in three ways.\n\
<subheading>The first way of imperfecting the breve.</subheading>\n\
In the first way, with respect to the whole only, and this in major or minor modus of either kind, perfect tempus, and minor prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The second way of imperfecting the breve.</subheading>\n\
In the second way, with respect to the neighbouring parts only, and this in major or minor modus of either kind, imperfect tempus, and major prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>The third way of imperfecting the breve.</subheading>\n\
In the third way, with respect to the whole and the neighbouring parts at once, and this in major or minor modus of either kind, perfect tempus, and major prolation, as is clear here:\n\
{example}</chapter>\n\
<chapter><heading>On the single way of imperfecting the semibreve. Chapter 7 [vii]</heading>\n\
The semibreve can be imperfected in a single way, namely with respect to the whole only, and this in major prolation under any kind of modus and tempus, because then it is worth three minims, of which one will be able to be subtracted as being a third part of the semibreve, as is clear in this example:\n\
{example}</chapter>\n\
<chapter><heading>On the three signs of imperfection. Chapter 8 [viii]</heading>\n\
Finally, because there are some established signs by which notes are recognized as being imperfected, I think it necessary to say something about these. Whence it must be understood that there are three signs that indicate that an imperfectible note is imperfected, namely imperfection in number, filling in of a note, and division by dot.\n\
<subheading>On the first sign of imperfection.</subheading>\n\
As to the first: whenever smaller notes are found set out in imperfect number either before or after a larger note, it is a sign that the first larger one imperfectible by them is to be imperfected, unless they should first be regrouped with their associates, as is clear in the following example:\n\
{example}\n\
<subheading>On the second sign of imperfection.</subheading>\n\
As to the second: whenever a whole note is filled in, it is a sign that it is imperfected by a third part of its whole value; and if a half part only of the note is filled in, it is a sign that it is imperfected by a third part of half its value. Also, smaller notes that imperfect larger ones in this way must be filled in just like them; nor does it matter whether the former precede or follow the latter, mediately or immediately, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
If, on the other hand, three like notes are filled in as a sign of imperfection, whether they are placed immediately one after the other or not, the middle one imperfects the first from behind and the last from ahead as united neighbouring parts, as is clear here:\n\
{example}\n\
And since the filling in of notes signifies not only imperfection, but also regrouping, sesquialtera, and dupla, I have comprehensively explained in my <citation>Proportionale musices</citation> how to tell with ease which of these four indications must be adopted when such filling in of notes is encountered in any piece of music; on which account I say nothing on this in the present treatise.\n\
<subheading>On the third sign of imperfection.</subheading>\n\
As to the third: whenever a dot of division is applied to any note either on its own behalf only or on behalf of itself and others, it is a sign that the first larger one imperfectible by them is to be imperfected, unless they should first be regrouped with their associates, as is clear here:\n\
{example}</chapter></book>\n\
<conclusion><heading>The conclusion of this work</heading>\n\
And these things said on the imperfections of musical notes should suffice; in which, if anything should be found to have been set down imperfectly, I pray that all those perfected in this divine art may be willing to perfect it as with a more perfect love, so that God himself, Lord of all knowledge, who knows no need of imperfection, may deem them worthy of being rewarded with his most perfect blessing.</conclusion>\n\
<explicit>Here ends the treatise on the imperfections of musical notes.</explicit></treatise>';
